SIMPLE: justify
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Justify
<hw>Jus"ti*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Justified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Justifying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>justifier</ets>, L. <ets>justificare</ets>; <ets>justus</ets> just
+ <ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make. See <er>Just</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>, and <er>-fy</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To prove or show to be just; to vindicate; to
maintain or defend as conformable to law, right, justice, propriety, or
duty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That to the height of this great argument⟦br⟧
I may assert eternal providence,⟦br⟧
And <qex>justify</qex> the ways of God to men.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Unless the oppression is so extreme as to <qex>justify</qex>
revolution, it would not <qex>justify</qex> the evil of breaking up a
government.</q> <rj><qau>E. Everett.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pronounce free from guilt or blame; to declare or
prove to have done that which is just, right, proper, etc.; to absolve;
to exonerate; to clear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I can not <qex>justify</qex> whom the law condemns.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <def>To treat as if righteous and
just; to pardon; to exculpate; to absolve.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By him all that believe are <qex>justified</qex> from all things,
from which ye could not be <qex>justified</qex> by the law of Moses.</q>
<rj><qau>Acts xiii. 39.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To prove; to ratify; to confirm.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>To make even or true, as lines
of type, by proper spacing; to align (text) at the left (left justify)
or right (right justify) margins of a column or page, or at both
margins; to adjust, as type. See <er>Justification</er>, 4.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To show (a person) to
have had a sufficient legal reason for an act that has been made the
subject of a charge or accusation.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To qualify
(one's self) as a surety by taking oath to the ownership of sufficient
property.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><q>The production of bail in court, who there <qex>justify</qex>
themselves against the exception of the plaintiff.</q>
<rj><qau>Bouvier's Law Dict.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To defend; maintain; vindicate; excuse;
exculpate; absolve; exonerate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Justify</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Justify
<hw>Jus"ti*fy</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld>
<def>To form an even surface or true line with something else; to fit
exactly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To take oath to the ownership of
property sufficient to qualify one's self as bail or surety.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Justinian</ent>⟦br⟧
